I feel confident that luclin has provided at least a 50% boost in our potential damage over time (if we invest in all the related skills and aquire the gear), and a 40-50% boost in our potential damage on full burn.<br>
<br>
And nobody talks about this, but our maximum dps during full burn has probably improved a lot as well; Garrison's Superior Sundering does 262 dps; 291 if you get the &quot;fast-casting nukes&quot; skill. Factor in 13% crits and it's 329 dps. Compare that to chaining Draught of Ice, which is somewhere just under 240dps (assuming you shave the recast delay to an absolute minimum).  Ratio is 1.37:1. About a 40% burndown-dps increase in the raw.<br>
<br>
And I already know what you're going to say about aggro =)<br>
But we're clearly winners in that field as well. Check this out:<br>
<br>
We could do up to 329 dps with Garrison's... but for aggro purposes you factor out the crits (no added aggro by all accounts) and factor in casting subtlety (assuming you care to get it)... 232.8 dps of aggro.<br>
<br>
Versus 240 pre-luclin with draught.<br>
<br>
i.e. our net aggro can actually go DOWN, even as our dps goes up!<br>
<br>
If you factor in an enchanter with aggro-modifying spells (which I suspect wizards will be first in line to recieve, due to the fact that we can make the most use of them during their short duration) it gets even better!<br>
A properly equipt enchanter could improve our aggro reduction from 20 to 50%. Now we're burning at 329 dps for an aggro of just 145 dps!<br>
Not to mention the same enchanter is boosting the tank's aggro level by 20% or so...<br>
<br>
And on top of all that, all of these aggro bonuses make Concussion more efficient because it scales with them.<br>
For example, say you critical on a Garrison's spell; 4200 damage (woot!). Now say you have casting subtlety and an enchanter aggro buff active.<br>
<br>
Now, from what I've heard, Concussion only counts for about 400 points of aggro; ie less than 1/10th of the nuke you just landed...<br>
But the nuke you just landed didn't cost 4200 aggro; it cost 1050 - so instead of concussion clearing 10% of your aggro, it will clear 40%.<br>
Leetness!<br>
<br>
So to sum things up:<br>
unlike before, where our real dps was a far cry from optimal due to aggro, in luclin not only does our raw potential damage increase, but so does our capacity to exercise it.<br>
<br>
So in reality, we may be talking about more than even 50% boost to net effectiveness here. We may be talking close to double.<br>
<br>
Have other classes recieved similar boosts? Are we still disadvantaged? I don't know; and that's a question for another place and time.<br>
<br>
I can easily picture rogues using their 'escape' skill to immense advantage on boss mobs; fight the mob to half health with ragebringer (for its concussion) then escape to clear aggro and finish the fight with your highest dps weapons while practically aggro-immune... but we'll just have to wait and see how much of a factor this tactic really is.<br>
<br>
As far as wizards are concerned, measured only against ourselves, it looks to me like we've seriously gone up several notches.<br>
I play my wizard with the long run in mind, and imho the long run just got much brighter for wizards. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/usamadhibots.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Samadhi BotS</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><table width=111><tr><td style=filter:glow(color=#6633FF strength=1);font-family:arial;font-weight;bold;font-size:'1pt' nowrap><font size=1 color=#FFFFFF face=Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif>Forum Censor !!!</font></td></tr></table></span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/27/02 9:42:54 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Random damage percentages?</span><hr size=1> I think I'll move this to the Library soon, I'll leave it here until Tuesday to let everyone get their last info in. <p><P align=center>
